@Noz Yes, and Dragon Age was tedious as well because of it. look if you don't agree with me, just move along and ignore my criticism, but don't be an apologist.

Every single media outlet has unanimously praised them and no one tells them to their faces the blatant flaws of the game. These flaws  killed the experience for many, including me.

I mean, this is a game that sold almost a million copies worldwide, in today's market that cannot be considered a decent amount, specially since it was released on a system with an install base of 100 million. If they ever wish to improve their sales numbers, they need to improve their game design choices, like square enix may be finally doing (I haven't played 15 yet, so who knows, I might be wrong on this).

@Noz I thought you were trying to say "its ok because Dragon Age does it too".

You want to know what I mean with interaction? I mean immersion into the world, something that makes you interested in the world other than its looks, and inviting mechanic to make that gigantic space fell less empty or useless.

I was thinking of Fallout 3 or the Fallout games in general, since we are making comparisons. Fallout's world rewards you of your exploration efforts, the Xenoblade games do not, you just get pretty backgrounds. Zelda is another good example as well.
